The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings originate, counted from the first drafts for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its corporate mini-kindergarten.
In wise anticipation, because most of his 90 employees are in the Babyboom age and the company is interested in the fact that the projectants return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work in a shortened way, the kindergarten is another bonus Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (contributions of CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment were procured and for a period of 2 years qualified staff and operation are provided.
After the utilization of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with Economy Rating providing active assistance in the implementation of the application.
The children are cared for by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but the day changes over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is about individual education and care, the programme content in the Mini Kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, but also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company milieu.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is eliminated when the children are picked up late from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus ranks among the Czech companies, which offer clear benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are cracked fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colours, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colours and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and bars.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which was executed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The Casa Batlló apartment building, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
On its drawing board the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where other works by Antoni Gaudí are located.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "yawning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces for the house, which was unique for the time.
A little bizarre, her 45-degree tilt already seems to be.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was not deceived by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so appalled at the completion that they demanded a remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also stumbled upon the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, no changes were made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city's request for this to be made, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy during more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí's reconstruction also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two other floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the atriums is impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was discovered that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, even extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price of visiting the monument is not a papier stalk, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes receive a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon turrets, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
