More and more parents want human surveillance devices to have the kids under control
The fear for one's own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, originally invented to search for cars, can locate people just as well, which would also be helpful in such cases, as in the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about as large as a cigarette box but soon it will not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have put the case of the disappeared Anička in fear and terror, and so they look for ways and means to protect their children better.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases such devices can be misused, for example if you put it in someone's pocket without him knowing about it, but so far we have not had such a case."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they do not want to be controlled."
"At the beginning, the mobile phones already aroused great expectations among the parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned kidnappings, the kidnapper practically always checks whether the child has any electronics with it that could be used to locate it."
