The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of supporters of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp fall last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both figures are the same as last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts to increase democracy.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and have recovered rapidly.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America of this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only marginally in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
But from country to country there are strong differences in mood (see diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
This is less so in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more noticeable and violent crime has increased.
Only for the second time since the start of the survey do many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were the victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economies: about 71% of respondents across the region said that the private sector is essential for development, and in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
Around 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared with 47% last year.
