Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the whole of the European Union.
Market tensions have triggered a dual response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary work companies or the lifting of the EUR 426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which collides with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro in line with German proposals, which means more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the requirements; possible suspension of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time now, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform off its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of drifting apart between what Germany considered necessary (strict fiscal plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was put by the Central European country, when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, Merkel comes out with a clear position in the last few days of October, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be saved while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, albeit a little sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It says to everyone that - even if unpopular measures need to be taken now - there will no longer be the old functioning of the euro from this date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the countries that are infringing will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a tough growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was cited by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we'd do bad not to understand.
It is not just a question of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero also understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like something would change.
Among the possibilities considered, we need to leave the euro area, which is full of little serious countries, not to be excluded.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The supposed exclusion of two players in the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being spilled over whether it was an unportable act or not and whether maybe both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next play phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules, but followed in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case presented is due to the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who, in his hymn Edelmut and Honor, had punished his players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the leading role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a rule circumvention. Indeed, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
On this matter, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players get an unjustified benefit from the opposing team. That, too, did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by false play or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but rather it should be as conspicuous as possible in order for it to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not put in a less favourable position, nor did he claim advantages for the game, because the obvious result of this action was that his own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, up to a certain degree uncertain, as the team could eventually withdraw. Moreover, players with this approach receive a sanction and pass into the second card cycle, in which they withdraw less than in the first cycle because of the accumulation of cards with a card.
So it is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such actions are not directed against the sport spirit, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent any sanction (this would be a clear case of rule avoidance), they preferred to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics arose from two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the kind of provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
