Global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in the greenhouse gas (CFC) which corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented in order to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments of the developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFC released to the earth due to the lighting would be avoided if the white glowing pears, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, by light emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases from the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the large exhaust emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
The compact fluorescent bulbs reduce energy consumption by 75%, while the new LED bulbs reduce this energy requirement by twice.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by Philips this week - this company, by the way, has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white glowing bulb, which suggests the savings possibilities of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that its completely new light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and therefore they have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide an acceptance point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in purchasing electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
