France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) fulfil their commitments 100% with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends € 1 to fulfil its obligations, France will give just 10 cents and it will be a comparable commitment.
Nice hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double swindle: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France succeeds in making it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, as the developing countries do not let themselves be completely deceived...
